res.send(): It’s generic. Express looks at what you’re sending (a string, an object, a buffer) and tries to "guess" the Content-Type header for you. If you pass a string, it sets it to text/html. If you pass an object, it actually calls res.json() internally anyway.

res.json(): It’s explicit. It forces the Content-Type header to application/json. It also converts non-objects (like null or undefined) into valid JSON.

